04588nam a22008775i 9780814744215DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t19971997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147442157 a10.18574/97808147442152doi  a(DE-B1597)547700  a(OCoLC)782877979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aAM11 .D46 1997 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a069.09731 aDennett, Andrea Stulman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWeird and Wonderful :bThe Dime Museum in America /cAndrea Stulman Dennett. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. The Origins of the Dime Museum, 1782-1840 -- t2. Barnum and the Museum Revolution, 1841-1870 -- t3. The Peak Years: From the Civil War to 1900 -- t4. Freaks and Platform Performers -- t5. Lecture Room Entertainments -- t6. Waxworks and Film -- t7. The Dime Museum Reconfigured for a New Century -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A. Chronology -- tAppendix B. Dime Museums -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDioramas and panoramas, freaks and magicians, waxworks and menageries, obscure relics and stuffed animals--a dazzling assortment of curiosities attracted the gaze of the nineteenth-century spectator at the dime museum. This distinctly American phenomenon was unprecedented in both the diversity of its amusements and in its democratic appeal, with audiences traversing the boundaries of ethnicity, gender, and class. Andrea Stulman Dennett's Weird and Wonderful: The Dime Museum in America recaptures this ephemeral and scarcely documented institution of American culture from the margins of history. Weird and Wonderful chronicles the evolution of the dime museum from its eighteenth-century inception as a "cabinet of curiosities" to its death at the hands of new amusement technologies in the early twentieth century. From big theaters which accommodated audiences of three thousand to meager converted storefronts exhibiting petrified wood and living anomalies, this study vividly reanimates the array of museums, exhibits, and performances that make up this entertainment institution. Tracing the scattered legacy of the dime museum from vaudeville theater to Ripley's museum to the talk show spectacles of today, Dennett makes a significant contribution to the history of American popular entertainment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aCuriosities and wondersxMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDime museumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEccentrics and eccentricitiesxMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 4aWeird. 4aWonderful. 4aamusement. 4acabinet. 4acentury. 4achronicles. 4acuriosities. 4adeath. 4adime. 4aearly. 4aeighteenth-century. 4aevolution. 4afrom. 4ahands. 4ainception. 4amuseum. 4atechnologies. 4atwentieth. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814744215423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814744215.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK